00:22:15,993 --> 00:22:21,922
You can't entirely depend on that because you don't know what forces are against you.

194
00:22:23,923 --> 00:22:26,827
It's no good me wanting to become prime minister.

195
00:22:28,970 --> 00:22:32,153
There's got to be a sort of realism about the desire.

196
00:22:32,213 --> 00:22:33,355
You have to test it.

197
00:22:33,635 --> 00:22:34,576
You have to be tested.

198
00:22:35,979 --> 00:22:39,163
But in terms of the obsessiveness we have,

199
00:22:39,463 --> 00:22:50,496
Around desires, you see, we overcome them by coming off the dream world and sitting in the midst of that turbulence, that strong desire, the addiction.

200
00:22:51,336 --> 00:23:02,167
And the thing is that our habits are the whole habit of clinging on to something, an attachment of having to have, must have, all that.

201
00:23:02,768 --> 00:23:09,015
Once you tackle the real tough nut, it all fades away because it's all one attitude.

202
00:23:09,855 --> 00:23:15,304
You don't have to go from this obsession to that obsession and then all the way down the line.

203
00:23:15,683 --> 00:23:19,249
If you hit the big one, they all begin to fade.

204
00:23:19,269 --> 00:23:24,395
And that's a bit of a blessing because we'll be here for lifetimes trying to get rid of it.

205
00:23:24,415 --> 00:23:29,564
So if you go for the big one, you see, then everything begins to be undermined.

206
00:23:31,767 --> 00:23:37,855
And what we're trying to do, and this is why the eating that we're doing here, the exercise around eating is so important.

207
00:23:38,195 --> 00:23:39,778
What we're trying to discover is

208
00:23:40,230 --> 00:23:48,980
How can I be with pleasure, with the joys of life, with a loving relationship, without this attachment, see?

209
00:23:49,000 --> 00:23:53,746
Without this obsessiveness, without this need, you see?

210
00:23:53,766 --> 00:24:00,373
And what we're doing is we're not just breaking away from those things we're dependent on.

211
00:24:00,973 --> 00:24:10,203
By finding this position within ourselves of the objective observer, we're actually discovering a new identity, see?

212
00:24:10,807 --> 00:24:24,749
We're taking the identity out of the body with its sensations, out of the heart with its emotions, out of the mind with its thoughts, and very slowly we're beginning to identify with something which is much deeper within us, which is our Buddha nature.

213
00:24:25,830 --> 00:24:33,942
And the more you identify with that which knows, the less you become needy for the world to give you happiness.

214
00:24:34,604 --> 00:24:38,490
Because you're finding your resting place in the one who knows, the Buddha within.

215
00:24:39,892 --> 00:24:39,971
See?

216
00:24:40,896 --> 00:24:47,924
And part of that process is to let go of the world as a place where we can find true happiness.

217
00:24:48,325 --> 00:25:01,799
Not to confuse these passing happinesses and joys and pleasures of life with real, sustainable, unchangeable, unalloyed, non-suffering, as the Buddha would have it.

218
00:25:03,122 --> 00:25:04,442
That's his way of putting happiness.

219
00:25:04,963 --> 00:25:07,586
He prefers to tell you what it isn't.

220
00:25:09,209 --> 00:25:10,329
Because as soon as you say,

221
00:25:10,511 --> 00:25:13,515
Well, Nirvana's happiness, everybody thinks it's some sort of blissed-out state.

222
00:25:15,175 --> 00:25:16,156
But it's not.

223
00:25:16,176 --> 00:25:23,183
Now, you know what it is because when you're meditating in that state of the pure observer, you're actually it.

224
00:25:23,785 --> 00:25:25,566
But you may not have recognized it.

225
00:25:26,968 --> 00:25:31,811
You may not have recognized the absolute peace and stillness that there is within the observer.

226
00:25:37,698 --> 00:25:38,898
You don't look as though you believe me.

227
00:25:41,410 --> 00:25:54,048
So anyway, that's all to do with this business of attachment and indulgence, addiction, compulsive behavior.

228
00:25:56,230 --> 00:26:00,478
The next business, of course, is this area of aversion.

229
00:26:00,498 --> 00:26:01,920
And of course, this is much the same.

230
00:26:02,480 --> 00:26:08,328
You find yourself in a dream world, you're hating people, you're chopping their heads off, all that sort of stuff.

231
00:26:08,798 --> 00:26:12,262
And then you just note, you know, anger, hatred.

232
00:26:12,743 --> 00:26:17,150
Or you're full of sort of anxiety, worrying about this, worrying about that, you know.

233
00:26:17,569 --> 00:26:22,557
These days, people might be worried about financial problems, losing their jobs.

234
00:26:22,576 --> 00:26:25,622
I mean, it's not a pleasant place to be in at the moment.

235
00:26:26,301 --> 00:26:28,085
And so you get these anxieties.

236
00:26:28,105 --> 00:26:30,008
You see, you note it, you come back.

237
00:26:30,448 --> 00:26:35,915
And as you go down to the breath, you feel, you get into those feelings, okay?

238
00:26:36,596 --> 00:26:37,438
So this again...

239
00:26:37,654 --> 00:27:05,063
is the other side of this attachment it's the other side of this wrong identity you see and just by tackling the big one you see where you feel most aversion and where you feel most fear that you're undermining that whole attitude of being averse to the world to people of being afraid of it so it's the same it's the same technique just coming off the dream

240
00:27:05,599 --> 00:27:33,362
feeling the fear you know that book feel the fear and do it anyway so that's it just feel the fear now of course in both of these cases as it's true for all the other hindrances you're also being aware of your relationship so how when when something good comes up we see the relationship of indulgence wanting it grabbing it so when it comes to things like hatred and well hatred also

241
00:27:33,612 --> 00:27:37,957
And cruelty, we want to indulge, yeah?

242
00:27:37,997 --> 00:27:46,926
We don't like to accept that, but being hateful can be very satisfying.

243
00:27:47,768 --> 00:27:52,292
Being angry, hurting somebody can bring quite a bit of internal joy.

244
00:27:54,796 --> 00:27:55,656
Fear is different.

245
00:27:55,676 --> 00:27:56,657
You panic with fear.

246
00:27:56,678 --> 00:28:01,284
So remember that when fear comes up, you want to be aware of the fear of fear.

247
00:28:01,304 --> 00:28:02,505
There's your panic, hmm?

248
00:28:03,176 --> 00:28:14,507
And so long as you can keep the two in mind, the two there within your observation, and just keep breathing in and out, wait for that fear of fear to go, you see, and the panic stops, and you're with fear.

249
00:28:15,207 --> 00:28:28,959
And the more we get used to the texture of fear, see, that's why it's so important to come into the body, off the mind, you get into the texture of fear, the feel of it, the nausea, the trembling of it, you know, and then you lose your fear of it.

250
00:28:28,979 --> 00:28:31,641
And then, of course, it's not fearful anymore.

251
00:28:31,661 --> 00:28:32,981
I mean, what's going to frighten us?

252
00:28:33,686 --> 00:28:36,490
When we've lost our fear of fear, what can frighten us?

253
00:28:37,431 --> 00:28:38,932
But it's getting beyond that barrier.

254
00:28:40,454 --> 00:28:44,799
And you do it always by sinking into, feeling the fear.

255
00:28:45,740 --> 00:28:47,342
So again, this is the Buddha's language.

256
00:28:47,823 --> 00:28:50,766
To feel feelings in feelings.

257
00:28:50,786 --> 00:28:51,707
That's the way he puts it.

258
00:28:51,727 --> 00:28:54,230
To feel, to know the body in the body.

259
00:28:54,289 --> 00:28:58,394
To know mental states in mental states.

260
00:29:06,474 --> 00:29:12,423
With all these dream factors, when you come back off the dream and you come into the body and you're feeling the...

261
00:29:12,903 --> 00:29:16,208
There has to be a very clear decision that you're not going to go back there.

262
00:29:16,868 --> 00:29:28,263
See, if you don't, if it's a sort of semi-decision, especially with those things that we like to indulge, whether it's an averse thing or an indulgent thing, then there's that leakage of desire.

263
00:29:29,605 --> 00:29:35,554
And so you've come off something, you see, and you come away noting, noting, I don't know...

264
00:29:36,007 --> 00:29:37,528
Well, we'll go back to romance, you see.

265
00:29:37,568 --> 00:29:40,991
Then you come back, but actually there's a part of you that still wants to go there.

266
00:29:41,011 --> 00:29:41,172
See?

267
00:29:41,633 --> 00:29:43,974
You've not actually said no to this leakage.

268
00:29:44,476 --> 00:29:47,898
So there you are feeling, whoop, and off you go again, you see.

269
00:29:47,919 --> 00:29:50,582
So it takes a moment of mindlessness.

270
00:29:50,821 --> 00:29:56,448
One millisecond of mindlessness coming off the subject and you're away.

271
00:29:57,108 --> 00:29:57,368
You see?

272
00:29:57,868 --> 00:30:00,711
So there has to be a clear recognition and acknowledgement.

273
00:30:01,032 --> 00:30:03,615
And as you turn away, there must be a decision.

274
00:30:03,934 --> 00:30:05,457
You don't want to go back there.

275
00:30:05,773 --> 00:30:08,337
And that stops that leakage of desire.

276
00:30:09,740 --> 00:30:10,540
See, that's important.

277
00:30:10,621 --> 00:30:17,049
So if you find yourself in a sitting and you're constantly going back to this dream thing, it may be just restlessness.

278
00:30:17,130 --> 00:30:19,553
It may be just the power of that desire.

279
00:30:19,953 --> 00:30:24,901
But just see if you've made a real decision not to go back into that dream space.

280
00:30:30,969 --> 00:30:34,413
Just passing over the third one, which is normally this donus and lethargy.

281
00:30:34,714 --> 00:30:37,017
And next after that is restlessness, you see.

282
00:30:37,038 --> 00:30:38,759
Restlessness is sort of catch-all.

283
00:30:39,460 --> 00:30:41,501
And in a sense, you've got to be very patient.

284
00:30:41,923 --> 00:30:48,068
If the mind is constantly in a state of just agitation, agitation, you see, then you've just got to be patient, you see.

285
00:30:48,108 --> 00:30:49,830
It's just this energy in the mind.

286
00:30:50,952 --> 00:30:54,476
And sometimes, you know, you think you're going mad, you see.

287
00:30:54,957 --> 00:30:56,578
And you are mad when you are mad.

288
00:30:57,179 --> 00:31:02,545
And so you just have to note, you know, restlessness, madness, and then just keep coming back to the breath.

289
00:31:02,862 --> 00:31:07,729
And if that's all you do, the whole sitting, the whole day, the whole week, that's the practice.

290
00:31:08,609 --> 00:31:14,598
So you don't think to yourself, well, I've sat here for 40 minutes just saying madness, madness, and trying to get back to my breath.

291
00:31:14,618 --> 00:31:16,020
It's absolutely useless, you see.

292
00:31:16,080 --> 00:31:16,701
No, it's not.

293
00:31:16,781 --> 00:31:17,624
That's the practice.

294
00:31:18,505 --> 00:31:20,708
If you note madness and you think, well, why not?

295
00:31:20,748 --> 00:31:21,328
Let's go mad.

296
00:31:21,469 --> 00:31:22,089
And off you go.

297
00:31:22,130 --> 00:31:23,071
That's bad.

298
00:31:23,291 --> 00:31:24,354
You should feel terrible.

299
00:31:24,933 --> 00:31:27,538
You should really feel guilty and horrible.

300
00:31:29,381 --> 00:31:29,540
See?

301
00:31:29,882 --> 00:31:30,102
But

302
00:31:30,554 --> 00:31:31,234
That's the practice.

303
00:31:31,255 --> 00:31:32,236
Keep coming off the mind.

304
00:31:32,256 --> 00:31:37,522
Keep coming off the mind, you see, until that energy has exhausted itself because that's where the energy has gone.

305
00:31:37,542 --> 00:31:38,403
It's gone into the head.

306
00:31:38,423 --> 00:31:39,204
What can you do?

307
00:31:40,307 --> 00:31:41,107
Same with the body.

308
00:31:41,208 --> 00:31:54,326
If you feel tremendously restless and you really want to move, you see, one thing you can do is to just feel sensations from the top of the head going down to the feet and just keep going from the top downwards, you see.

309
00:31:54,705 --> 00:31:56,848
That tends to calm the body a bit, you see.

310
00:31:57,410 --> 00:31:59,952
But don't do it entirely for the purpose of

311
00:32:00,305 --> 00:32:01,385
calming the body.

312
00:32:01,465 --> 00:32:03,909
Do it to see where restlessness is.

313
00:32:05,070 --> 00:32:07,554
Did you ever feel restless at the end of your nose?

314
00:32:07,574 --> 00:32:09,256
Very difficult.

315
00:32:09,276 --> 00:32:10,116
It doesn't happen.

316
00:32:10,656 --> 00:32:15,983
So you have to sort of come down the body, where you feel the restlessness, hang on a little bit, keep moving, you see.

317
00:32:16,163 --> 00:32:18,205
And that also stops the mind wandering too.

318
00:32:21,410 --> 00:32:25,394
And with that there's this other business of guilt, shame, remorse.

319
00:32:26,276 --> 00:32:28,117
So

320
00:32:28,637 --> 00:32:55,522
again these things have to be felt and often it's because we've left things undone we might have hurt somebody and we've not apologized it might be that somebody's hurt us and you've not told them you've not forgiven them so those are processes that you can do in your sitting if you find for instance a lot of guilt coming up over something you've done you see then

321
00:32:55,907 --> 00:33:23,568
stay with the guilt you see but then write yourself a note and say well when I leave this is what I'll do and that puts that to rest at least for a while until you've put right what you did wrong if there's a lot of hate and vengefulness over somebody who's hurt you you see then you know feel feel it feel it feel it you see and then write yourself a note see that you know you'll approach the person then when you leave if of course the person is unapproachable either

322
00:33:23,801 --> 00:33:38,984
either because they're not to be found or they've died or something, then, of course, you have to, in a sense, do a little ritual for yourself, you see, of writing a letter, doing something whereby you can externalize this problem.

323
00:33:39,144 --> 00:33:40,166
It helps, that's all.

324
00:33:40,547 --> 00:33:48,479
But eventually, it's actually coming into those feelings, you see, and resting with them.

325
00:33:48,499 --> 00:33:50,923
There's a whole load of stuff around that area which...

326
00:33:51,847 --> 00:33:54,131
I tend not to tackle until the end of the week.

327
00:33:54,191 --> 00:34:01,240
So if that stuff comes up and you find it difficult to handle, then just come and see me.

328
00:34:05,445 --> 00:34:06,788
Then there's skeptical doubt.

329
00:34:07,388 --> 00:34:12,436
Now this is really pernicious in any part of our lives.

330
00:34:12,456 --> 00:34:17,382
Pernicious doubt, skeptical doubt, is that doubt which stops you doing something.

331
00:34:17,402 --> 00:34:18,023
That's what it does.

332
00:34:18,043 --> 00:34:19,105
It stops you doing something.

333
00:34:19,507 --> 00:34:27,773
So if you're applying for a job and there's this constant, well, I don't know whether I can, maybe I shouldn't, I don't know whether I could, you see, before you've decided the job's gone.

334
00:34:29,076 --> 00:34:33,559
If you get into a relationship and you think, well, maybe I can't live, maybe I'm not, I don't know whether I should, it's gone.

335
00:34:34,199 --> 00:34:36,521
It's gone away, isn't it?

336
00:34:36,541 --> 00:34:38,344
And you can't commit yourself.

337
00:34:38,463 --> 00:34:40,226
That's what skeptical doubt does, you see.

338
00:34:40,885 --> 00:34:47,251
Now, the fact that you've all come here and you're all meditating means that there can't be much skeptical doubt about meditation, you see.

339
00:34:47,992 --> 00:34:59,608
but it has its little ways, you know, like, for instance, the main one that people suffer from, I think we all suffer from, to some degree, is doubt about ourselves, doubt as to whether we can make progress in this practice.

340
00:35:00,789 --> 00:35:08,760
You know, you look around, everybody's sitting very, very still, and you think, well, I can't sit still, even though everybody's looking at you saying, my God, you're sitting still.

341
00:35:09,842 --> 00:35:12,465
But we have all this sort of doubt going on about ourselves.

342
00:35:13,326 --> 00:35:15,989
So when that sort of doubt comes up, you know,

343
00:35:16,239 --> 00:35:45,099
just remind yourself of the Buddhist teaching it's a psychological it's a spiritual imperative that everybody all beings will become liberated all beings it's a spiritual imperative because that's the way consciousness is moving just because it's not moving fast enough doesn't mean it's not moving and often in our practice we go through times when it's very dreary like a desert

344
00:35:45,552 --> 00:36:15,541
nothing seems to be happening where we seem to be putting a lot of effort in and not getting any real results see so those are testing times you just got to keep going see until until you move through it and often it's caused by you know false expectation I was once when I was in Birmingham a man turned up to do some meditation at the center and he said when he first came on a retreat this is going back a bit to the late 70s

345
00:36:15,742 --> 00:36:22,170
he was going on a course, okay, it's a course, a meditation course, in which one achieved Nibbana.

346
00:36:23,010 --> 00:36:27,056
So he went to this course and he thought, you know, Saturday, Sunday, that's it, I'll have made it.

347
00:36:30,278 --> 00:36:38,068
As the time rolled on, you know, and it came to the end, there was this, God, you know, we didn't turn him off, we came back and did some more.

348
00:36:38,829 --> 00:36:40,871
But that's what we think, we think, oh, you know,

349
00:36:41,375 --> 00:36:45,038
I keep doing this for a while, things will get so much better.

350
00:36:45,057 --> 00:36:47,159
I'll be liberated and all this sort of stuff.

351
00:36:47,179 --> 00:36:52,864
But, of course, these expectations eventually undermine our practice because they're not real.

352
00:36:53,465 --> 00:36:54,005
They're not real.

353
00:36:56,068 --> 00:37:01,731
So be careful about expecting something from the practice, you see.

354
00:37:01,871 --> 00:37:06,096
We have to have a certain faith that there is purification going on.

355
00:37:07,356 --> 00:37:10,739
There is wisdom slowly being formed.

356
00:37:11,159 --> 00:37:38,230
it's just as soon as you enter into that position of the observer it has to happen it can't not be happening see as soon as you're there taking that position of observing of feeling things of allowing things to manifest you see there must be some small change within our looking it's like a like i said before it's like like chinese torture you know the drip the drip torture and slowly

357
00:37:38,411 --> 00:38:07,811
there are little aha moments you see when finally the penny drops a bit it's very rare for somebody to have a sort of cosmic you know opening where everything sort of bursts into light and one suddenly rises up in the air it's very most times it's just this plodding plodding plodding and then when you look back over time you know 5, 6, 10 years you say things have changed so it's a slow process the Buddha

358
00:38:08,128 --> 00:38:09,510
The Buddha warned us, it's gradual.

359
00:38:09,851 --> 00:38:10,311
There's nothing...

360
00:38:10,911 --> 00:38:17,117
I know you hear in certain traditions the sudden enlightenment and the, what is it, sudden and gradual enlightenment.

361
00:38:17,797 --> 00:38:26,625
But these are misunderstandings because when an insight comes, of course it's sudden.

362
00:38:26,644 --> 00:38:27,885
An insight doesn't take time.

363
00:38:28,065 --> 00:38:29,467
You either see it or you don't see it.

364
00:38:30,208 --> 00:38:32,931
But to get there can be one hell of a journey.

365
00:38:32,951 --> 00:38:34,152
So it depends where you're standing.

366
00:38:34,652 --> 00:38:37,815
If you're standing in the insight, yes, it's sudden enlightenment.

367
00:38:38,351 --> 00:38:42,722
But if you're standing outside the insight, you're blooming gradual.

368
00:38:42,983 --> 00:38:43,123
Right?

369
00:38:43,143 --> 00:38:48,195
So all those arguments about sudden and gradual insight seem to me to be a bit silly, really.

370
00:38:49,818 --> 00:38:51,483
Nobody here, I hope.

371
00:38:53,748 --> 00:38:55,112
Going to the Zen school.

372
00:38:58,012 --> 00:39:02,498
Then there's of course doubt in the teaching, doubt in the Buddha and all that.

373
00:39:03,079 --> 00:39:14,673
And really that again is undermined through the practice and through reading and through thinking about it and reflecting on the teaching and making sure that we understand what the Buddha's talking about.

374
00:39:15,614 --> 00:39:19,621
And through our practice it becomes realistic.

375
00:39:19,840 --> 00:39:20,561
And that's it, you see.

376
00:39:20,641 --> 00:39:27,411
So here we're understanding all this business about defilements, about mental states that are

377
00:39:27,998 --> 00:39:29,300
that are difficult to work with.

378
00:39:32,403 --> 00:39:34,106
And then of course there's doubt in the teacher.

379
00:39:34,427 --> 00:39:35,208
Heaven forbid.

380
00:39:38,072 --> 00:39:44,882
And of course that has to be tested because the teacher in Buddhism is only there to guide.

381
00:39:45,342 --> 00:39:49,809
It's not a faith in the teacher in that guru sense.

382
00:39:49,909 --> 00:39:52,132
That would be really undermining the process.

383
00:39:52,893 --> 00:39:54,815
See the Buddha himself, he couldn't handle that.

384
00:39:55,335 --> 00:39:58,842
Just before he died, there was a young monk who looked upon him mooningly.

385
00:39:59,362 --> 00:40:00,403
He sent him off to the forest.

386
00:40:01,144 --> 00:40:01,887
He's on his deathbed.

387
00:40:01,907 --> 00:40:07,536
This is when he's, you know, he saw that he'd got this wrong relationship with, you know, the Buddha.

388
00:40:07,556 --> 00:40:08,056
Sent him off.

389
00:40:08,237 --> 00:40:10,641
Get out.

390
00:40:10,661 --> 00:40:18,452
So it's not that sort of, you know, this sort of whatever we mean by a guru relationship.

391
00:40:18,512 --> 00:40:19,715
It's not meant to be that at all.

392
00:40:19,775 --> 00:40:21,478
It's meant to be someone who is,

393
00:40:21,829 --> 00:40:24,873
just giving instructions, pointing to the moon, as they say.

394
00:40:24,913 --> 00:40:26,054
The Buddha points to the moon.

395
00:40:27,135 --> 00:40:29,016
He shouldn't be looking at the end of his finger.

396
00:40:33,320 --> 00:40:34,621
So, skeptical doubt.

397
00:40:34,842 --> 00:40:37,244
That's something just to be aware of.

398
00:40:37,965 --> 00:40:42,307
And again, when you go into it, you see, you may find it's just fear.

399
00:40:42,648 --> 00:40:43,849
Fear of failure.

400
00:40:44,710 --> 00:40:45,871
Fear of criticism.

401
00:40:47,172 --> 00:40:51,836
Usually it's some sort of fear down there, which stops us making that commitment.

402
00:40:52,356 --> 00:40:58,722
This often comes up when I offer people the opportunity to take refuges and precepts.

403
00:41:00,224 --> 00:41:08,632
It's the same, the distinction between, shall we say, a partnership and marriage.

404
00:41:09,074 --> 00:41:12,157
Somebody explained to me once there was a difference between bacon and eggs.

405
00:41:13,097 --> 00:41:15,179
Have you heard that?

406
00:41:15,199 --> 00:41:21,485
See, when it comes to eggs, the chicken gives of its egg, but the pig gives of its life.

407
00:41:22,445 --> 00:41:51,675
so there is something about a marriage which is like it's a further giving of oneself and it's not surprising to me to find that often people who've been in a partnership for quite some time finally decide to get married go through an actual ceremony of marriage you see I've done that for a few people and it just points out that so long as it's just a partnership see there's always this clause

408
00:41:52,684 --> 00:41:53,925
Underneath it gets you out.

409
00:41:54,827 --> 00:41:58,829
But the point of a marriage is a complete commitment to the other, you see.

410
00:41:59,490 --> 00:42:01,992
You know, like we had this lovely wedding, you see.

411
00:42:02,112 --> 00:42:04,275
Sickness and health are poor for rich.

412
00:42:04,414 --> 00:42:04,976
It doesn't matter.

413
00:42:05,076 --> 00:42:07,617
You're committed to the person entirely, you see.

414
00:42:07,637 --> 00:42:12,963
And that, of course, is an act of compassion, you see.

415
00:42:12,983 --> 00:42:17,646
It's an act of complete giving of oneself to the other, you see.

416
00:42:18,327 --> 00:42:21,831
Of course, it works as long as the other is giving their complete self to you.

417
00:42:23,025 --> 00:42:25,851
Once that begins to separate, then you're stuck.

418
00:42:28,695 --> 00:42:30,838
So, skeptical doubt, yeah?

419
00:42:30,978 --> 00:42:32,722
So be careful of that.

420
00:42:32,742 --> 00:42:35,106
Again, be careful of what the mind's doing, you see?

421
00:42:35,306 --> 00:42:35,927
Be aware of it.

422
00:42:37,831 --> 00:42:41,135
Two things I haven't, well, one thing I haven't looked at is boredom.

423
00:42:41,697 --> 00:42:48,949
So remember, boredom comes under the heading of aversion, and it's important for us because the boredom comes up in the practice, you know?

424
00:42:49,536 --> 00:43:05,981
I mean, if you put it out in the ordinary world that you just spent a whole week trying to observe the breath, you see, they would probably think, well, you know, I can't think of anything more boring than watching my breath and feeling the breath arising and passing away.

425
00:43:06,623 --> 00:43:12,431
So when boredom comes, you see, remember, this is the product of indulgence.

426
00:43:12,873 --> 00:43:13,172
Okay?

427
00:43:13,914 --> 00:43:17,619
So remember there are five, five, uh,

428
00:43:18,190 --> 00:43:45,108
negatives that come up there's an aftermath from indulgence and once you connect these two once you connect this then of course you tend to come off at least gross indulgence a gross dependency so there's addiction there's compulsive behaviour there's frustration when you don't get it there's grief when you lose it you're always afraid of losing so you take out an insurance policy and boredom

429
00:43:46,523 --> 00:43:52,550
remember when the Buddha was fully liberated, for seven years, Mara chased him with his three daughters.

430
00:43:53,010 --> 00:43:53,210
See?

431
00:43:53,871 --> 00:43:58,336
Sensual desire, sexual desire, and boredom.

432
00:43:58,356 --> 00:43:58,856
Interesting, eh?

433
00:43:59,878 --> 00:44:09,128
Now, of course, what that story is telling us is that there were still remnants in his mind for seven years of old habits.

434
00:44:09,148 --> 00:44:09,909
See?

435
00:44:09,929 --> 00:44:10,891
Of seeking happiness.

436
00:44:10,971 --> 00:44:15,096
But Mara goes away, you see, slinking away, saying, the Buddha sees me.

437
00:44:15,599 --> 00:44:27,610
So even though there were still these, what's known as vasana, in the Buddha's mind, even after he was liberated, which took seven years to completely die out, there were still these three things, you see.

438
00:44:28,050 --> 00:44:29,112
And boredom is there.

439
00:44:29,492 --> 00:44:32,956
So boredom is a state of aversion, right?

440
00:44:32,976 --> 00:44:37,000
Not wanting, seeking excitement.

441
00:44:37,019 --> 00:44:38,161
And that's what it tells you to do.

442
00:44:38,240 --> 00:44:41,523
It tells you to seek divertissement.

443
00:44:41,543 --> 00:44:44,126
It tells you to seek excitement, you see.

444
00:44:44,146 --> 00:44:45,487
But what you do with boredom is

445
00:44:45,907 --> 00:45:15,525
is repetition you feel the boredom and you keep repeating what you're doing so this is true for anything in life whether you're trying to learn an instrument work at work where boredom arises you see because you're doing the same thing day in and day out or whatever you see so you recognize the boredom and you just keep doing what you're doing you don't indulge the boredom you don't seek distraction

446
00:45:19,505 --> 00:45:23,588
All these things that we're talking about, they all pertain to ordinary day life.

447
00:45:23,628 --> 00:45:26,512
You can't just do them when you come on retreat.

448
00:45:26,731 --> 00:45:28,152
It's just constant.

449
00:45:28,172 --> 00:45:31,516
It's terrible, but there we are.

450
00:45:31,536 --> 00:45:35,380
And then finally, there's our two very good friends, dullness and lethargy.

451
00:45:36,862 --> 00:45:41,286
Or if you want to put a moral twist on them, sloth and torpor.

452
00:45:43,148 --> 00:45:47,672
Now, we have to make a distinction between tiredness

453
00:45:48,023 --> 00:45:52,708
where the body needs rest, the mind needs rest, and this dullness and lethargy.

454
00:45:53,528 --> 00:46:10,710
So tomorrow, for instance, we get up a little earlier, and there may be still some remnants of tiredness from when you first came, because virtually everybody rides on a retreat with some sleep imbalance.

455
00:46:10,929 --> 00:46:14,134
Either they are oversleeping or they're undersleeping.

456
00:46:14,213 --> 00:46:15,414
They're not sleeping well, see?

457
00:46:15,715 --> 00:46:19,760
And it normally takes three or four days for that to slowly iron itself out.

458
00:46:20,500 --> 00:46:23,423
So tomorrow, getting up a little earlier, just pushes the system a bit.

459
00:46:24,525 --> 00:46:27,648
But we shall struggle.

460
00:46:27,728 --> 00:46:32,934
And then by the fourth day, of course, there's massive energy, and one wonders where it was all before.

461
00:46:32,994 --> 00:46:38,621
Now, how is it we have this conditioning of dullness and lethargy?

462
00:46:38,661 --> 00:46:41,925
So just consider how many times

463
00:46:42,512 --> 00:46:46,097
you have indulged in that subliminal state of sleep.

464
00:46:47,697 --> 00:46:54,606
Just, you know, hanging around at the weekend in bed on that lovely level where you're neither asleep nor awake.

465
00:46:56,146 --> 00:47:03,695
Where you've taken a newspaper to bed or you're listening to the radio and you just keep wafting in and out into these pleasant states.

466
00:47:05,918 --> 00:47:06,038
Yeah?

467
00:47:06,057 --> 00:47:06,157
Yeah?

468
00:47:06,592 --> 00:47:13,420
How many times when you feel a bit depressed, a bit low, a bit down, you've just flung yourself onto the couch and just fallen asleep for a while?

469
00:47:14,681 --> 00:47:18,346
So, in other words, it's a way that we get rid of ourselves.

470
00:47:18,925 --> 00:47:22,429
It's a way that we can annihilate ourselves.

471
00:47:23,271 --> 00:47:25,813
Of course, we wouldn't do it if we didn't think we were going to wake up.

472
00:47:27,315 --> 00:47:31,199
But it's a way that we keep pushing ourselves into this state of oblivion.

473
00:47:31,920 --> 00:47:34,983
And the reason why we do it is because there's no suffering there.

474
00:47:35,003 --> 00:47:36,144
There's no suffering in oblivion.

475
00:47:36,782 --> 00:48:06,233
unfortunately we'll wake up what we hope is that on waking all the troubles will have gone so it's actually a small way in which we commit suicide that's what we're doing we're getting rid of the self every time we use sleep to annihilate ourselves we're actually desiring non-becoming so the Buddha points to three desires sensual desire the desire to become

476
00:48:06,483 --> 00:48:31,271
and the desire not to become so that it is in us always when it gets too heavy a desire to escape and one way we escape is fall asleep so what we're suffering from when we have this dullness in the mind like porridge and the body feels as heavy as lead and all that is the consequence of these indulgences what do we do?

477
00:48:31,572 --> 00:48:36,338
we refuse to be annihilated absolutely completely and utterly refuse

478
00:48:36,824 --> 00:49:06,291
we use noting to keep ourselves awake you can come up the body up from your toes to the top of the head just keep the attention moving so there's energy being displaced into that looking that process and you're looking to see where is it that you feel this heaviness you feel it in your toes you feel it in your knees see where is it and if you keep coming upwards like that it just keeps the energy coming up you see and you're able to

479
00:49:06,574 --> 00:49:35,416
stay awake within that state when it comes to the body feels great but the mind is just full of this heavy dullness like big fog or smog then just roam around it roam around it feeling it seeing it you see and you might be surprised to find that you wake up like a bulb right in the middle of that fog I'm sure you've all experienced that surely of course you have so why do I ask these questions so

480
00:49:36,088 --> 00:50:04,206
and you wake up completely bright and alert in the middle of this dullness in the middle of this awesome smog and that just shows you that what's actually making us become the dullness is association with the dullness it's an association it's an identity with the feelings of lethargy and the more you move around in it the more you're pulling out of it the more you're trying to

481
00:50:04,456 --> 00:50:21,052
investigate the taste of it, the feel of it, the texture of it, the more this knowing is awakening until eventually it wakes up completely and it's like you're there in the middle of this smoke, this heaviness.

482
00:50:22,032 --> 00:50:23,393
And it's a mental state.

483
00:50:23,673 --> 00:50:34,023
It's as valid a mental state as depression, anxiety, all these things that we have a no-no on, this is also a no-no.

484
00:50:34,273 --> 00:50:34,534
Right?

485
00:50:34,914 --> 00:50:37,538
It's an awesome state to be in.

486
00:50:37,918 --> 00:50:44,686
So when you get to that point, what you're allowing is this energy to dissipate.

487
00:50:45,226 --> 00:50:47,668
And it's an energy that's like a whirlpool.

488
00:50:47,708 --> 00:50:49,510
It's drawing you down into the black hole.

489
00:50:50,672 --> 00:50:54,536
It's not these other energies that are swishing you out into galaxies.

490
00:50:55,557 --> 00:50:55,918
See?

491
00:50:55,938 --> 00:50:57,039
This is mirrored in nature.

492
00:50:57,059 --> 00:50:58,340
It's quite remarkable, really.

493
00:50:58,945 --> 00:51:04,992
So as soon as you feel yourself being washed down into this black hole, make sure that you lift yourself up.

494
00:51:05,293 --> 00:51:06,134
Keep awake, you see.

495
00:51:06,875 --> 00:51:08,717
And you can open your eyes, let the light in.

496
00:51:08,818 --> 00:51:09,577
You can stand up.

497
00:51:09,898 --> 00:51:14,664
You see, if it gets too much, then just gently leave the meditation hall.

498
00:51:14,684 --> 00:51:15,385
Do some walking.

499
00:51:16,867 --> 00:51:19,030
I've walked for hours up and down with this stuff.

500
00:51:20,311 --> 00:51:24,177
It used to, at one point, it used to last for ten days, just up and down, up and down.

501
00:51:24,577 --> 00:51:28,782
One point I was doing the times table, I got as far as 17 going forwards and backwards.

502
00:51:28,842 --> 00:51:30,065
Can you imagine that?

503
00:51:30,085 --> 00:51:32,248
I knew the 17 times table backwards.

504
00:51:32,987 --> 00:51:34,190
Not bad, you know.

505
00:51:34,210 --> 00:51:35,692
And that was just to keep myself awake.

506
00:51:35,711 --> 00:51:42,480
When I said this to my teacher, Janica, he said, it's very good, he said, better to think of the Dharma.

507
00:51:45,023 --> 00:51:46,686
Spent all my time learning these times tables.

508
00:51:48,166 --> 00:51:51,851
So just the effort of just staying above it, you know, that's all.

509
00:51:52,101 --> 00:51:53,784
I'm not so sure that was all that skillful.

510
00:51:53,804 --> 00:51:57,909
It would have been perhaps more skillful to do this investigation more.

511
00:51:57,929 --> 00:52:00,132
But it was just the effort to stay awake, to stay awake.

512
00:52:01,393 --> 00:52:02,775
So there's a lot of it.

513
00:52:03,235 --> 00:52:06,820
All this stuff that we've talked about, unfortunately, there's sort of mountains of it.

514
00:52:07,561 --> 00:52:08,702
But we struggle on, you see.

515
00:52:09,483 --> 00:52:10,344
We continue.

516
00:52:14,068 --> 00:52:16,692
So that really covers...

517
00:52:17,465 --> 00:52:24,853
all our negativity really, you know, if I've missed it, then you can, I think, if I've missed something, you'll be able to slot it in to one of those five.

518
00:52:25,175 --> 00:52:26,155
Okay?

519
00:52:26,175 --> 00:52:42,838
All those things to do around indulgence and pleasure, all those things to do around aversion and hatred and fear, all those things, all those feelings and stuff we have to do around dullness and lethargy, all the restlessness, the guilt, shame, remorse, and finally, skeptical doubt.

520
00:52:42,858 --> 00:52:43,038
See?

521
00:52:43,217 --> 00:52:47,083
That covers, that covers the whole range of stuff that we have to deal with.

522
00:52:48,733 --> 00:53:02,431
And just to repeat, our job is to recognize it, to point to it, to know what it is, to know what to do about it, so that we undermine them, and eventually they stop altogether.

523
00:53:02,452 --> 00:53:06,956
So the Buddha is liberated from all that, he's liberated from that suffering.

524
00:53:07,358 --> 00:53:13,565
Somebody who is fully liberated doesn't have these kilesa, they're gone.

525
00:53:15,248 --> 00:53:16,750
He doesn't suffer from them anymore.

526
00:53:18,367 --> 00:53:19,889
So the future looks bright.

527
00:53:24,436 --> 00:53:27,539
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

528
00:53:27,559 --> 00:53:47,208
May you be liberated from all suffering by your acute and unrelenting practice undermining these dreadful hindrances sooner rather than later.

529
00:53:48,168 --> 00:53:50,364
I can't make them feel good either.

